  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Blaise Ag\u00fcera y Arcas's article \"What Is Intelligence?\" has made a significant impact in the academic community, as evidenced by its citation count of 1,644, reflecting a strong influence in scholarly discussions on intelligence.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in an unspecified venue, \"What Is Intelligence?\" by Blaise Ag\u00fcera y Arcas from Google has garnered substantial acknowledgment within the academic literature, achieving an impressive citation count of 1,644. This metric illustrates how the work has effectively resonated within contemporary discussions surrounding the concept of intelligence, positioning it as a pivotal academic resource.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article, which has successfully undergone peer review and has been formally published, demonstrates the authors' commitment to disseminating their research within the scientific community. The combined impact of both the preprint and final published version is reflected in its high citation rates, suggesting that the research has actively enabled subsequent discourse and exploration in related fields.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the absence of online mentions and community discussions on platforms such as Wikipedia or Reddit, the significant citation metrics underscore the scholarly relevance of Ag\u00fcera y Arcas's work. This path of recognition highlights its integral role in shaping academic narratives and framing ongoing debates within the paradigm of intelligence research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, \"What Is Intelligence?\" exemplifies a robust academic contribution, evident through its extensive citations and the clear impact it has had on further scholarly inquiry in understanding intelligence. This article serves as a foundational piece for researchers and practitioners alike as they navigate the complexities of this multifaceted concept.</p>",
